\begin_layout Section
The ECB's Survey of Professional Forecasters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The European Central Bank (ECB) carries out a quarterly survey of expectations
 for the rate of inflation among professional economists and institutions,
 known as the Survey of Professional Forecasters (SPF).
 Though the format of the SPF has changed over time, in every SPF since
 1999Q1, a panel of professional forecasters has been asked to provide their
 expectations of annualized HICP Euro Area inflation at the end of the current
 calendar year, the next calendar year, and the calendar year five years
 ahead.
 Recent SPFs have also included forecasts for the end of the calendar year
 after next.
 The ECB releases the expectations of all surveyed forecasters at every
 horizon included in the SPF, indexing the forecasts by the forecaster who
 provided them; in effect, the SPF represents distributional data on the
 distribution of inflation expectations at discrete future points in time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pricing of many financial securities (Treasury inflation-protected securitie
s, for instance) depends on inflation expectations over time.
 Given the vast array of inflation-linked securities in the marketplace,
 the forecast horizons of the SPF may be too coarse to be useful for pricing
 and other purposes: for instance, we may be interested in the distribution
 of inflation expectations halfway through a calendar year.
 This is a natural arena in which we may ask questions of inference and
 imputation given distributional data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We formalize the modeling problem as follows.
 Suppose the expectation 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 for annualized HICP Euro Area inflation at time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 conditional on today's inflation evolves continuously according to some
 stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dX_{t}=\mu_{\theta}(X_{t})dt+\sigma_{\theta}(X_{t})dW_{t}\label{eq:cond-inf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a Wiener process.
 We may conceptualize this as a scenario in which we have a uncountable
 sample space of forecasters, each with her own model for the evolution
 of inflation over time.
 For any particular forecaster 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is the conditional expectation for inflation at time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 of forecaster 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 given today's inflation.
 Note that we are not modeling the evolution of inflation over time; rather,
 we are modeling the evolution of inflation expectations.
\end_layout

