\begin_layout Section
Modeling Inflation Expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin our study by supposing that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cond-inf"

\end_inset

 is specified according to an OU diffusion i.e.
 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\theta}(x)=-\lambda(x-\mu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\theta}(x)=\sigma$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(\mu,\lambda,\sigma)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a convenient specification since the transition density of the
 OU diffusion is available, and thus we are able to check the consistency
 of the MKLDE obtained through MCEM against the MKLDE obtained through direct
 maximization of the analytic average log-likelihood.
 
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I can outline exactly how to calculate this if needed, not sure if too pedantic.
\end_layout

\end_inset

For each SPF in our data set, we carry out MKLDE using both the direct maximizat
ion method and the proposed MCEM scheme, fixing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 as the annualized HICP Euro Area inflation reported at the most recent
 month before the quarter that the SPF was distributed (the SPF is usually
 distributed in the first month of each quarter, so we can assume forecasters
 are conditioning on the inflation print of the previous month).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:mle-vs-mcem"

\end_inset

 reports the results of both direct maximization and of MCEM on the dataset,
 when we measure time in quarterly units.
 We note that the MKLDEs for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 obtained by MCEM using approximate bridges are effectively indistinguishable
 from those obtained via direct maximization of the analytic likelihood.
 On the other hand, the bias is non-trivially positive for the MKLDE of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, suggesting that the thin-tailedness of the approximate bridges can in
 fact affect the quality of MKLDEs obtained by MCEM in empirical situations.
 The computational cost of running MCEM with exact bridges, however, is
 still high enough that the practitioner will need to weigh the utility
 of slightly more accurate estimates against significantly longer running
 times on a case-by-case basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MKLDE for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 aligns closely with intuition: the ECB's inflation targeting policy states
 that it aims for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inflation rates of below, but close to, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\%$
\end_inset

 in the medium term
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Forecasters on average then, are merely reverting to the medium-term goal
 of the ECB when reporting their long-term conditional expectations for
 inflation.
 The directly obtained MKLDE for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 suggests that the conditional inflation expectations of forecasters revert
 to the ECB's target inflation rate by 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\times(\mbox{Current Inflation}-1.94\%)$
\end_inset

 every quarter.
 
\end_layout

