\begin_layout Standard
With the ability to find the MKLDE for each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N=68$
\end_inset

 SPFs, we can experiment to see how well the OU diffusion models the evolution
 of inflation expectations relative to a baseline linear interpolation method.
 
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I will outline the exact method of making these baseline linear interpolations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, we attempt to interpolate inflation expectations at horizons
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-4$
\end_inset

 quarters and 
\begin_inset Formula $7-10$
\end_inset

 quarters, which are available in every SPF in the data set, using the closest
 neighboring horizons.
 For example, interpolation of a forecast 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 quarters ahead would use the current value of inflation and the forecast
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 quarters ahead.
 Our imputation method is as follows.
 For each SPF, we estimate the MKLDE once witholding the 
\begin_inset Formula $1-4$
\end_inset

 quarter forecast and once withholding the 
\begin_inset Formula $7-10$
\end_inset

 quarter forecast.
 Then, we simulate generalized OU bridges governed by the MKLDE between
 the closest neighboring horizons, and take the values of these bridges
 at the time corresponding to the forecast of interest.
 To evaluate the performance of our imputation method against a linear interpola
tion, we compute the sample K-L divergence using the estimator of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "perez-cruz-2008"

\end_inset

.
 In order to use this estimator, we must add normally distributed noise
 with small variance 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma^{2}\approx0.001)$
\end_inset

 to the linear interpolations and the true SPF forecasts, so that there
 are no repeated values.
 We drop any negative estimates of the K-L divergence, and present the distribut
ions of the divergences across the SPFs in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:est_kl"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

