\begin_layout Standard
We see that the generalized OU bridges offer an imputed distribution noticeably
 closer to the true distribution at the 
\begin_inset Formula $1-4$
\end_inset

 month horizon, while the linear interpolation performs comparably at the
 
\begin_inset Formula $7-10$
\end_inset

 month horizon.
 More precisely, the mean K-L divergence from the distribution reported
 in the SPFs at the 
\begin_inset Formula $1-4$
\end_inset

 month horizon is 
\begin_inset Formula $1.10$
\end_inset

 when used bridge-based imputation and 
\begin_inset Formula $1.56$
\end_inset

 when using linear interpolation.
 However, in general, the K-L divergences remain fairly large: for reference,
 the standard Gaussian distribution and the standard Exponential distribution
 are estimated to have K-L divergence of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $0.7$
\end_inset

.
 The observed K-L divergences of either imputation method therefore appear
 to suggest that conditional expectations of inflation do not evolve either
 linearly or according to an OU process over time; this is expected, since
 there is no reason to think that the conditional expectations should even
 follow time-homogenous dynamics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nevertheless, the methodology proposed here can provide a useful first step
 in thinking about the evolution of inflation expectations over time.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:cont_path"

\end_inset

, we present a visualization of the final product of this thesis.
 Using the proposed MCEM scheme to estimate the MKLDE, we repeatedly sample
 generalized bridges between the SPF forecast distributions, whose dynamics
 are governed by the MKLDE.
 Examination of this figure reveals that an OU process does seem like a
 poor fit, especially at short horizons—the up-and-down during the first
 quarter suggests that the forecasters expected inflation to remain low
 in the short-term, and rapidly accelerate in the medium-term.
 The inability to capture dynamics like these leads our generalized OU bridges
 to mean-revert 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too quickly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, before being forced to come back down to the SPF forecasts for one quarter
 forward.
 
\end_layout

